1 3. The Board shall meet at least twice a year, but no more than
2 four (4) times a year and shall elect a chair and a vice-chair vice
3 chair from among its members. The Board shall only meet as required
4 for:
5 a. election of officers,
6 b. establishment of meeting dates and times,
7 c. rule development,
8 d. review and recommendation, and
9 e. adoption of nonbinding resolutions to the Board
10 concerning matters brought before the Board.
11 4. Special meetings may be called by the chair or by
12 concurrence of any three members.
13 B. 1. All members of the Board shall be knowledgeable of
14 counseling issues. The Board shall be appointed by the Governor
15 with the advice and consent of the Senate:
16 a. four members who are licensed professional counselors,
17 b. three members who are licensed family and marital
18 therapists,
19 c. two members who are licensed behavioral practitioners,
20 and
21 d. two members representing the public and possessing
22 knowledge of counseling issues.
23 2. Members of the Board shall serve for a period of three (3)
24 years and may be removed at any time by the appointing authority.
ENGR. S. B. NO. 397 Page 2

1 Vaca ncies on the Board shall be filled by the appointing authority.
2 A majority of the Board shall constitute a quorum for the
3 transaction of business.
4 3. The members of the Board from each professional area of
5 behavioral health counseling shall comprise separate committees and
6 shall consult on professional issues within their respective areas
7 of behavioral health counseling. Each committee shall recommend to
8 the Board approval or disapproval of all licenses to be issued
9 within its specialty. Each committee shall be authorized to
10 recommend approval or disapproval of the examination requirements
11 for all applicants for licensure in the respective area of
12 behavioral health counseling, provide grading standards for
13 examinations, and provide for other matters relating to licensure in
14 that area of behavioral health counseling. Each committee may
15 create advisory committees to consult on professional duties and
16 responsibilities pursuant to the provisions of this section.
17 4. Any and all recommendations, approvals, or disapprovals made
18 by a committee pursuant to the provisions of this section shall not
19 become effective without the approval of a majority of members of
20 the Board.
21 5. The jurisdictional areas of the Board shall include
22 professional counseling licensing and practice issues, marital and
23 family therapist licensing and practice issues, behavioral
24
